'''Koide Clan''' (小出氏) was a Japanese samurai and noble family. The clan rose to prominence during the [[Azuchi–Momoyama period]] under the patronage of [[Toyotomi Hideyoshi]], becoming a daimyo family. They ruled the {{ill|Sonobe Domain|ja|園部藩|12=draft}} in {{ill|Tanba Province|ja|丹波国|12=draft}} until the abolition of the feudal domain system during the [[Meiji Restoration]], after which they were ennobled as Viscounts in the [[Kazoku]] peerage system.

== Origins ==
The Koide Clan claims descent from the [[Nikaido clan]] of the [[Southern Fujiwara]] lineage, tracing their roots to {{ill|Koide Village|ja|小出村|12=draft}} in the {{ill|Ina District, Nagano|ja|上伊那郡|12=draft}} of [[Shinano Province]]. According to the {{ill|Azuma Kagami|ja|吾妻鏡|12=draft}}, members of the clan served in various roles for the Kamakura shogunate, including ceremonial horse-handlers. Other sources, such as the {{ill|Hyakka Keizu Ko|ja|百家系図稿|12=draft}}, suggest a connection to the {{ill|Kudo clan|ja|工藤氏|12=draft}}.

The clan's prominence began with [[Koide Hideyasu]], who became the husband of [[Toyotomi Hideyoshi]]'s maternal aunt, securing favor and territory under the Toyotomi regime. In 1585, Hideyasu was granted [[Kishiwada Castle]] in {{ill|Izumi Province|ja|和泉国|12=draft}} with a stipend of 30,000 koku.

== History as Daimyo ==
The Koide family continued to serve under the Toyotomi and later the Tokugawa regimes. Hideyasu's son, [[Koide Yoshimasa]], was granted {{ill|Tatsuno Castle|ja|龍野城|12=draft}} in {{ill|Harima Province|ja|播磨国|12=draft}}. By 1595, the family was relocated to {{ill|Izushi Domain|ja|出石藩|12=draft}}, receiving 60,000 koku. Despite siding with the Western Army during the [[Battle of Sekigahara]], they avoided confiscation of their domain thanks to Yoshimasa's younger brother, who fought for the Eastern Army.

Over time, the Koide family's holdings were redistributed, and different branches governed {{ill|Kishiwada Domain|ja|岸和田藩|12=draft}} and {{ill|Sonobe Domain|ja|園部藩|12=draft}}. The Sonobe branch persisted until the Meiji Restoration.

== Koide Clan as Kazoku ==
After the Meiji Restoration, the head of the Sonobe branch, [[Koide Hidenao]], was appointed governor of Sonobe Domain. In 1884, his descendant [[Koide Hidefumi]] was ennobled as a Viscount under the Kazoku system. The family maintained their status as part of the Japanese nobility into the early 20th century.

== Family Crest ==
The Koide clan used the crests "Maruni-Gaku" (circle with a framed pattern) and "Gaku-ni-Nihachi-moji" (framed pattern with the characters for two and eight), along with an alternative crest, "Kikko-ni-Ko-no-ji" (hexagon with the character for 'Ko').

== Notable Members ==
* [[Koide Hideyasu]] – First daimyo of Kishiwada Castle
* [[Koide Yoshimasa]] – Daimyo of Tatsuno and Izushi
* [[Koide Hidenao]] – Last daimyo of Sonobe Domain

